tweet:
And that’s my intellectual art thread of the day lol 

Also rereading that it’s also symbolic of life lol. Just gotta get through that messy awkward stage and you’ll be ok in the end.

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: The key is perseverance. Just gotta push yourself through that messy ugly stage because in the end it will all come together. Oil painting is like sculpting, just constantly building up layers and almost molding the image. Just force yourself to keep going, it’ll be ok in the end

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: One problem I find with the painting process, is that for the longest time it’ll look like sh*t lol. Honestly. It’s starts out looking ok-ish and then as you build up more layers it looks messy af and that’s when the panic and frustration sets in.…

description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: There is more but that’s all I feel like writing. Tbh I have very mixed feelings. And since it’s autism acceptance month, I just ask for patience and understanding. I will screw up, a lot.  And apologize ahead of time for it.

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: Despite my difficulties I’ve been professionally successful. Before my current career I was working in veterinary medicine (vet’s assistant) and had considered going on further, but it was a very emotional job and I was unable to handle that. So I left to pursue tattooing.

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: I am overly emphatic and I have a very fixed view on what is right/wrong and what is fair. I often cry when I hear or see stories in the news. For example, I’m a vegetarian, and have been for many years, and will probably remain one for the rest of my life.

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: Despite my difficulty handling stress I am able to keep a cool head in a crisis...contradictory I know but it’s true. I’ve known what to do in a medical emergency before and am thankful for that

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: Perks tho. I know it helps me with my art. I can see the world differently, and I know that helps me draw/paint. I don’t know how, but it does. And I have a fantastic memory which helps me with details (I would do very well on Jeopardy). I am full of useless facts/info lol.

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: And I have my routines and it’s so important to me that I keep them. If anything changes last minute I meltdown. I will pace, I get angry, I cry.

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: But it’s ok. Because I have my comforts. I will watch movies/tv shoes over and over again if I love them. And I will play the same song on repeat for hours and days. Hyperfixation it’s called. When I say I love something, I love the hell out of it.

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: I am very impulsive, and that often goes along with my moods. I will confess I am difficult, very difficult, this I know. And for this reason I prefer to keep to myself

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: I’m like that in real life as well. If I’m too stressed out, or if I’m being yelled at or I’m in trouble, or if there’s too much noise I shutdown. I forget how to speak, or what to do.

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: I do get overwhelmed often. Especially if I get too many messages/comments/emails. I see them all, and I feel my mind start to go blank and I go mute. So if I don’t reply it’s more that my brain is overloading and I forget how to properly communicate.

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: I’m autistic. And I have adhd as well, and I suffer from severe anxiety and depression. Yeah. lol. It’s a constant struggle no lie but it is what it is.

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: I am not the most articulate so forgive me if i at any point sound confusing. I am not always capable of properly expressing my thoughts and ideas...which goes hand in hand with this I think...sorry I am rambling

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: @pud20 So I do recommend a heavier/thicker paper, such as bristol. And I always start out using a 2H pencil, to rough in the form, and then an HB to start adding detail, and then I’d go back with a 2B to darken up the shadow/darker areas.

tweet: I have gotten a few questions in the past about working with charcoal and also just drawing techniques in general, so I’ve done a spontaneous tutorial. Not sure if it’s any help but have a watch and I hope people can take something away from it x #ArtistOnTwitter https://t.co/fBMwwVr0V5

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: @tgemiles Think of it more like sculpting than drawing. You’re adding and taking away to form the face.

name: Kristin Wilkinson
description: She/Her   Tiny Canadian artist/Tattoo artist, #LFC supporter, #actuallyautistic, just trying my best
tweet: @tgemiles Smudging creates almost like a base coat/layer. But you don’t want to oversmudge, just lightly use a tissue to smooth it out. Once you’re done there, you go back with the pencils (charcoal here) and a putty eraser, and start building layers to shape the face.
